WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.300
CHAPTER XI of MEDITATIONS OF MARKUS ARRELIUS

00:18.920 --> 00:25.900
The Meditations of Marcus Aurelius by Marcus Aurelius Antoninus

00:25.900 --> 00:28.200
Translated by George Long

00:28.820 --> 00:30.420
CHAPTER XI

00:31.960 --> 00:34.780
These are the properties of the rational soul.

00:35.200 --> 00:40.880
It sees itself, analyzes itself, and makes itself such as it chooses.

00:41.580 --> 00:49.420
The fruit which it bears itself enjoys, for the fruit of plants and that in animals which corresponds to fruits others enjoy.

00:50.220 --> 00:54.680
It obtains its own end, wherever the limit of life may be fixed.

00:55.320 --> 01:03.760
Not as in a dance and in a play and in such like things, where the whole action is incomplete, if anything cuts it short.

01:04.280 --> 01:14.900
But in every part and wherever it may be stopped, it makes what has been set before it full and completes, so that it can say, I have what is my own.

01:15.720 --> 01:22.200
And further it traverses the whole universe and the surrounding vacuum and surveys its form.

01:22.760 --> 01:30.560
And it extends itself into the infinity of time and embraces and comprehends the periodical renovation of all things.

01:31.000 --> 01:38.760
And it comprehends that those who come after us will see nothing new, nor have those before us seen anything more.

01:39.400 --> 01:51.280
But in a manner he who is forty years old, if he has any understanding at all, has seen by virtue of the uniformity that prevails all things which have been and all that will be.

01:52.240 --> 02:03.980
This too is a property of the rational soul, love of one's neighbor, and truth and modesty, and to value nothing more than itself, which is also the property of law.

02:04.600 --> 02:09.060
Thus then, right reason differs not at all from the reason of justice.

02:11.960 --> 02:21.680
Thou wilt set little value on pleasing song and dancing in the pancreasium, if thou wilt distribute the melody of the voice into its several sounds,

02:22.140 --> 02:29.840
and ask thyself as to each if thou art mastered by this, for thou wilt be prevented by shame from confessing it.

02:29.840 --> 02:38.680
And in the matter of dancing, if at each movement and attitude thou wilt do the same, and the like also in the matter of the pancreasium.

02:39.680 --> 02:46.400
In all things then, except virtue and the acts of virtue, remember to apply thyself to their several parts,

02:46.960 --> 02:53.020
and by this division to come to value them little, and apply this rule also to thy whole life.

02:54.980 --> 03:06.160
What a soul that is which is ready, if at any moment it must be separated from the body, and ready to be extinguished, or dispersed, or continue to exist,

03:06.920 --> 03:14.220
but so that this readiness comes from a man's own judgment, not from mere obstinacy, as with the Christians,

03:14.780 --> 03:21.540
but considerably, and with dignity, and in a way to persuade another without tragic show.

03:23.880 --> 03:35.540
Have I done something for the general interest? Well then, I have had my reward. Let this always be present to thy mind, and never stop doing such good.

03:37.040 --> 03:43.340
What is thy art? To be good. And how is this accomplished well, except by general principles,

03:43.980 --> 03:49.220
some about the nature of the universe, and others about the proper constitution of man?

03:51.300 --> 03:58.220
At first tragedies were brought on the stage as means of reminding men of the things which happened to them,

03:58.580 --> 04:06.000
and that it is according to nature for things to happen so, and that if you are delighted with what is shown on the stage,

04:06.440 --> 04:10.060
you should not be troubled with that which takes place on the larger stage.

04:10.840 --> 04:17.460
For you see that these things must be accomplished thus, and that even they bear them who cry out, O Satheron.

04:18.180 --> 04:24.720
And indeed, some things are said well by the dramatic writers, of which kind is the following especially.

04:25.920 --> 04:31.360
Me and my children, if the gods neglect, this has its reason too.

04:31.960 --> 04:37.160
And again, we must not chafe and fret at that which happens.

04:38.760 --> 04:46.100
And, life's harvest reap like the wheat's fruitful ear, and other things of the same kind.

04:47.440 --> 04:53.460
After tragedy the old comedy was introduced, which had a magisterial freedom of speech,

04:53.900 --> 04:59.340
and by its very plainness of speaking was useful in reminding men to beware of insolence,

04:59.840 --> 05:03.400
and for this purpose too diogenes used to take from these writers.

05:04.600 --> 05:09.600
But as to the middle comedy which came next, observe what it was, and again,

05:09.600 --> 05:16.280
for what object the new comedy was introduced, which gradually sunk down into a mere mimic artifice.

05:17.080 --> 05:20.800
That some good things are said even by these writers everybody knows,

05:21.520 --> 05:26.220
but the whole plan of such poetry and dramaturgy, to what end does it look?

05:29.300 --> 05:35.520
How plain does it appear that there is not another condition of life so well suited for philosophizing

05:35.520 --> 05:38.780
as this in which thou now happenest to be.

05:40.620 --> 05:46.880
A branch cut off from the adjacent branch must of necessity be cut off from the whole tree also.

05:47.860 --> 05:53.520
So too a man when he is separated from another man has fallen off from the whole social community.

05:54.780 --> 06:01.480
Now as to a branch, another cuts it off, but a man by his own act separates himself from his neighbor

06:01.480 --> 06:06.940
when he hates him and turns away from him, and he does not know that he has at the same time

06:06.940 --> 06:09.360
cut himself off from the whole social system.

06:10.480 --> 06:14.020
Yet he has this privilege certainly from Zeus who frames society,

06:14.800 --> 06:18.580
for it is in our power to grow again to that which is near to us,

06:19.040 --> 06:22.280
and again to become a part which helps us to make up the whole.

06:23.180 --> 06:26.440
However if it often happens, this kind of separation,

06:26.440 --> 06:31.040
it makes it difficult for that which detaches itself to be brought to unity

06:31.040 --> 06:33.700
and to be restored to its former condition.

06:34.800 --> 06:38.940
Finally the branch, which from the first grew together with the tree

06:38.940 --> 06:41.420
and has continued to have one life with it,

06:41.900 --> 06:45.700
is not like that which after being cut off is then ingrafted,

06:45.920 --> 06:50.740
for this is something like what the gardeners mean when they say that it grows with the rest of the tree,

06:51.180 --> 06:53.760
but that it has not the same mind with it.

06:56.140 --> 07:01.560
As those who try to stand in thy way when thou art proceeding according to right reason,

07:02.060 --> 07:05.220
will not be able to turn thee aside from thy proper action,

07:05.920 --> 07:09.580
so neither let them drive thee from thy benevolent feelings towards them,

07:10.140 --> 07:12.640
but be on thy guard equally in both matters,

07:13.020 --> 07:15.640
not only in the matter of steady judgment and action,

07:16.080 --> 07:21.640
but also in the matter of gentleness towards those who try to hinder or otherwise trouble thee.

07:22.240 --> 07:25.520
For this is also a weakness, to be vexed at them,

07:25.780 --> 07:28.300
as well as to be diverted from thy course of action,

07:28.600 --> 07:30.120
and to give way through fear,

07:30.740 --> 07:33.160
for both are equally deserters from their post,

07:33.660 --> 07:35.260
the man who does it through fear,

07:35.680 --> 07:39.900
and the man who is alienated from him who is by nature a kinsman and a friend.

07:42.720 --> 07:45.660
There is no nature which is inferior to art,

07:46.120 --> 07:48.460
for the arts imitate the natures of things,

07:48.460 --> 07:52.640
but if this is so, that nature which is the most perfect

07:52.640 --> 07:55.400
and the most comprehensive of all natures,

07:55.660 --> 07:57.780
cannot fall short of the skill of art.

07:58.740 --> 08:02.620
Now all arts do the inferior things for the sake of the superior,

08:03.460 --> 08:06.340
therefore the universal nature does so too,

08:07.100 --> 08:10.040
and indeed hence is the origin of justice,

08:10.620 --> 08:13.680
and in justice the other virtues have their foundation,

08:13.680 --> 08:18.760
for justice will not be observed if we either care for middle things,

08:18.940 --> 08:23.840
things indifferent, or are easily deceived and careless and changeable.

08:26.440 --> 08:28.860
If the things do not come to thee,

08:29.280 --> 08:32.260
the pursuits and avoidances of which disturb thee,

08:32.700 --> 08:35.520
still in a manner thou goest to them,

08:36.240 --> 08:38.980
let then thy judgment about them be at rest,

08:39.300 --> 08:41.160
and they will remain quiet,

08:41.160 --> 08:45.160
and thou wilt not be seen either pursuing or avoiding.

08:47.560 --> 08:50.580
The spherical form of the soul maintains its figure,

08:51.040 --> 08:53.440
when it is neither extended toward any object,

08:53.780 --> 08:57.400
nor contracted inwards, nor dispersed, nor sinks down,

08:58.000 --> 09:01.920
but is illuminated by light, by which it sees the truth,

09:02.300 --> 09:05.940
the truth of all things, and the truth that is in itself.

09:08.720 --> 09:11.240
Suppose any man shall despise me,

09:11.760 --> 09:13.360
let him look to that himself,

09:14.060 --> 09:15.660
but I will look to this,

09:15.960 --> 09:20.340
that I be not discovered doing or saying anything deserving of contempt.

09:21.500 --> 09:24.620
Shall any man hate me, let him look to it,

09:24.820 --> 09:28.200
but I will be mild and benevolent towards every man,

09:28.720 --> 09:31.100
and ready to show even him his mistake,

09:31.700 --> 09:32.840
not reproachfully,

09:32.840 --> 09:35.880
nor yet as making a display of my endurance,

09:36.500 --> 09:39.680
but nobly and honestly like the great Phocion,

09:40.300 --> 09:42.480
unless indeed he only assumed it.

09:43.100 --> 09:45.720
For the interior parts ought to be such,

09:46.180 --> 09:48.400
and a man ought to be seen by the gods

09:48.400 --> 09:51.680
neither dissatisfied with anything, nor complaining.

09:52.720 --> 09:54.460
For what evil is it to thee,

09:54.760 --> 09:57.980
if thou art now doing what is agreeable to thy own nature,

09:58.560 --> 10:00.920
and art satisfied with that which at this moment

10:00.920 --> 10:03.180
is suitable to the nature of the universe,

10:04.120 --> 10:06.820
since thou art a human being placed at thy post,

10:07.280 --> 10:09.500
in order that what is for the common advantage

10:09.500 --> 10:11.340
may be done in some way.

10:12.940 --> 10:16.120
Men despise one another and flatter one another,

10:16.560 --> 10:19.380
and men wish to raise themselves above one another,

10:19.820 --> 10:21.860
and crouch before one another.

10:24.520 --> 10:27.660
How unsound and insincere is he who says,

10:27.660 --> 10:30.620
I have determined to deal with thee in a fair way.

10:31.440 --> 10:32.900
What art thou doing, man?

10:33.240 --> 10:35.220
There is no occasion to give this notice.

10:35.580 --> 10:37.620
It will soon show itself by acts.

10:38.520 --> 10:41.160
The voice ought to be plainly written on the forehead.

10:42.140 --> 10:43.840
Such as a man's character is,

10:43.880 --> 10:45.960
he immediately shows it in his eyes,

10:46.420 --> 10:49.300
just as he who is beloved forthwith reads everything

10:49.300 --> 10:50.580
in the eyes of lovers.

10:51.720 --> 10:55.140
The man who is honest and good ought to be exactly like a man

10:55.140 --> 10:58.140
who smells strong, so that the bystander,

10:58.140 --> 10:59.400
as soon as he comes near him,

10:59.680 --> 11:01.740
must smell whether he chews or not.

11:02.600 --> 11:05.900
But the affectation of simplicity is like a crooked stick.

11:06.580 --> 11:09.140
Nothing is more disgraceful than a wolfish friendship.

11:10.080 --> 11:11.740
Avoid this most of all.

11:12.160 --> 11:15.900
The good and simple and benevolent show all these things

11:15.900 --> 11:18.820
in the eyes, and there is no mistaking.

11:21.060 --> 11:23.040
As to living in the best way,

11:23.040 --> 11:25.040
this power is in the soul,

11:25.600 --> 11:28.120
if it be indifferent to things which are indifferent.

11:28.820 --> 11:30.180
And it will be indifferent,

11:30.400 --> 11:33.540
if it looks on each of these things separately and altogether,

11:33.540 --> 11:37.040
and if it remembers that not one of them produces in us

11:37.040 --> 11:40.180
an opinion about itself, nor comes to us.

11:40.540 --> 11:42.680
But these things remain immovable,

11:43.000 --> 11:46.740
and it is we ourselves who produce the judgments about them,

11:46.920 --> 11:50.060
and, as we may say, write them in ourselves,

11:50.060 --> 11:52.900
it being in our power not to write them,

11:53.060 --> 11:55.920
and it being in our power, if perchance these judgments

11:55.920 --> 11:58.800
haven't perceptibly got a mission to our minds,

11:59.260 --> 12:00.480
to wipe them out.

12:00.920 --> 12:04.420
And if we remember also that such attention will only be

12:04.420 --> 12:08.180
for a short time, and then life will be at an end.

12:09.180 --> 12:12.300
Besides, what trouble is there at all in doing this?

12:12.720 --> 12:15.880
For if these things are according to nature, rejoice in them,

12:16.020 --> 12:17.580
and they will be easy to thee.

12:17.580 --> 12:19.880
But if contrary to nature,

12:20.240 --> 12:22.580
seek what is conformable to thy own nature,

12:23.000 --> 12:26.500
and strive towards this, even if it bring no reputation,

12:27.060 --> 12:29.760
for every man is allowed to seek his own good.

12:32.680 --> 12:34.960
Consider whence each thing has come,

12:35.440 --> 12:38.580
and of what it consists, and into what it changes,

12:39.160 --> 12:42.200
and what kind of a thing it will be when it is changed,

12:42.680 --> 12:44.720
and that it will sustain no harm.

12:47.620 --> 12:51.300
If any have offended against thee, consider first.

12:52.500 --> 12:56.280
What is my relation to men, and that we are made for one another,

12:56.880 --> 13:00.080
and in another respect I was made to be said over them,

13:00.480 --> 13:03.340
as a ram over the flock, or a bull over the herd.

13:04.180 --> 13:07.380
But examine the matter from first principles, from this.

13:07.880 --> 13:12.120
If all things are not mere atoms, it is nature which orders all things.

13:12.620 --> 13:16.940
If this is so, the inferior things exist for the sake of the superior,

13:16.940 --> 13:19.540
and these for the sake of one another.

13:20.880 --> 13:25.400
Second, consider what kind of men they are at table, in bed, and so forth,

13:25.940 --> 13:30.460
and particularly, under what compulsions in respect of opinions they are,

13:30.760 --> 13:34.800
and as to their acts, consider with what pride they do what they do.

13:36.260 --> 13:41.140
Third, that if men do rightly what they do, we ought not to be displeased,

13:41.460 --> 13:45.800
but if they do not right, it is plain that they do so involuntarily,

13:45.800 --> 13:47.360
and in ignorance.

13:48.260 --> 13:51.780
For as every soul is unwillingly deprived of the truth,

13:52.300 --> 13:55.700
so also it is unwillingly deprived of the power of behaving

13:55.700 --> 13:58.780
to each man according to his deserts.

13:59.380 --> 14:03.400
Accordingly, men are pained when they are called unjust, ungrateful, and greedy,

14:03.840 --> 14:05.940
and in a word wrongdoers to their neighbors.

14:07.400 --> 14:11.460
Fourth, consider that thou also doest many things wrong,

14:11.880 --> 14:13.920
and that thou art a man like others,

14:13.920 --> 14:17.100
and even if thou dost abstain from certain faults,

14:17.480 --> 14:19.960
still thou hast the disposition to commit them,

14:20.380 --> 14:23.280
though either through cowardice or concern about reputation,

14:23.720 --> 14:27.160
or some such mean motive thou dost abstain from such faults.

14:28.500 --> 14:31.120
Fifth, consider that thou dost not even understand

14:31.120 --> 14:33.180
whether men are doing wrong or not,

14:33.540 --> 14:36.840
for many things are done with a certain reference to circumstances,

14:37.580 --> 14:40.280
and in short, a man must learn a great deal

14:40.280 --> 14:44.300
to enable him to pass a correct judgment on another man's acts.

14:47.060 --> 14:50.320
Sixth, consider when thou art much vexed or grieved

14:50.320 --> 14:52.580
that man's life is only a moment,

14:53.100 --> 14:56.420
and after a short time we are all laid out dead.

14:58.420 --> 15:02.040
Seventh, that it is not men's acts which disturb us,

15:02.360 --> 15:05.580
for those acts have their foundation in men's ruling principles,

15:05.580 --> 15:09.700
but it is our own opinions which disturb us.

15:10.440 --> 15:12.260
Take away these opinions then,

15:12.540 --> 15:15.220
and resolve to dismiss thy judgment about an act

15:15.220 --> 15:18.720
as if it were something grievous, and thy anger is gone.

15:19.500 --> 15:21.980
How then shall I take away these opinions?

15:22.460 --> 15:26.440
By reflecting that no wrongful act of another brings shame on thee.

15:27.160 --> 15:29.640
For unless that which is shameful is alone bad,

15:30.140 --> 15:33.120
thou also must of necessity do many things wrong,

15:33.120 --> 15:36.040
and become a robber and everything else.

15:37.780 --> 15:40.700
Eighth, consider how much more pain is brought on us

15:40.700 --> 15:44.240
by the anger and vexation caused by such acts

15:44.240 --> 15:48.640
than by the acts themselves at which we are angry and vexed.

15:49.660 --> 15:52.980
Ninth, consider that a good disposition is invincible,

15:53.540 --> 15:57.340
if it be genuine, and not an affected smile and acting apart.

15:58.360 --> 16:00.760
For what will the most violent man do to thee,

16:00.760 --> 16:04.160
if thou continuest to be of a kind disposition towards him,

16:04.420 --> 16:08.440
and if, as opportunity offers, thou gently admonishest him

16:08.440 --> 16:11.260
and calmly correctest his errors at the very time

16:11.260 --> 16:13.480
when he is trying to do thee harm, saying,

16:13.480 --> 16:18.020
Not so, my child, we are constituted by nature for something else.

16:18.400 --> 16:20.160
I shall certainly not be injured,

16:20.520 --> 16:22.900
but thou art injuring thyself, my child.

16:23.820 --> 16:28.320
And show him with gentle tact and by general principles that this is so,

16:28.320 --> 16:31.300
and that even bees do not do as he does,

16:31.460 --> 16:34.840
nor any animals which are formed by nature to be gregarious.

16:35.480 --> 16:38.820
And thou must not do this neither with any double meaning,

16:39.200 --> 16:42.120
nor in the way of reproach, but affectionately,

16:42.340 --> 16:44.380
and without any rancor in thy soul.

16:44.880 --> 16:47.140
And not as if thou were lecturing him,

16:47.500 --> 16:50.000
nor yet that any bystander may admire,

16:50.660 --> 16:53.380
but either when he is alone, and if others are present.

16:55.640 --> 16:57.280
Remember these nine rules,

16:57.660 --> 17:00.460
as if thou hast received them as a gift from the muses,

17:00.820 --> 17:04.440
and begin at last to be a man while thou livest.

17:05.580 --> 17:09.340
But thou must equally avoid flattering men and being vexed at them,

17:09.480 --> 17:11.840
for both are unsocial and lead to harm.

17:12.720 --> 17:15.680
And let this truth be present to thee in the excitement of anger,

17:16.040 --> 17:18.640
that to be moved by passion is not manly,

17:18.940 --> 17:20.800
but that mildness and gentleness,

17:20.800 --> 17:23.420
as they are more agreeable to human nature,

17:23.920 --> 17:26.080
so also are they more manly.

17:26.600 --> 17:31.440
And he who possesses these qualities possesses strength, nerves, and courage,

17:31.940 --> 17:35.760
and not the man who is subject to fits of passion and discontent.

17:36.480 --> 17:40.700
For in the same degree in which a man's mind is nearer to freedom from all passion,

17:41.360 --> 17:44.140
in the same degree also is it nearer to strength.

17:44.700 --> 17:47.760
And as the sense of pain is a characteristic of weakness,

17:48.340 --> 17:49.940
so also is anger.

17:49.940 --> 17:54.640
For he who yields to pain, and he who yields to anger,

17:55.140 --> 17:57.660
both are wounded, and both submit.

17:59.320 --> 18:04.820
But if thou wilt, receive also a tenth present from the leader of the muses, Apollo,

18:05.500 --> 18:10.240
and it is this, that to expect bad men not to do wrong is madness,

18:10.720 --> 18:13.620
for he who expects this desires an impossibility.

18:14.380 --> 18:16.880
But to allow men to behave so to others,

18:16.880 --> 18:21.540
to expect them not to do thee any wrong, is irrational and tyrannical.

18:24.320 --> 18:28.020
There are four principal aberrations of the superior faculty,

18:28.680 --> 18:31.280
against which thou shouldst be constantly on thy guard.

18:31.820 --> 18:35.540
And when thou hast detected them, thou shouldst wipe them out,

18:35.640 --> 18:37.200
and say on each occasion thus,

18:37.640 --> 18:39.300
This thought is not necessary.

18:39.860 --> 18:42.220
This tends to destroy social union.

18:42.900 --> 18:45.780
This which thou art going to say comes not from the real thoughts.

18:45.780 --> 18:49.500
For thou shouldst consider it among the most absurd of things,

18:49.900 --> 18:51.980
for a man not to speak from his real thoughts.

18:52.860 --> 18:55.960
But the fourth is when thou shalt reproach thyself for anything.

18:56.680 --> 18:59.340
For this is an evidence of the diviner part within thee,

18:59.680 --> 19:02.880
being overpowered, and yielding to the less honorable,

19:03.320 --> 19:07.500
and to the perishable part, the body, and to its gross pleasures.

19:11.020 --> 19:14.980
Thy aerial part, and all the fiery parts which are mingled in thee,

19:14.980 --> 19:17.580
though by nature they have an upward tendency,

19:18.280 --> 19:21.020
still in obedience to the disposition of the universe

19:21.020 --> 19:24.640
they are overpowered here in the compound mass, the body.

19:25.360 --> 19:28.620
And also the whole of the earthy part and the watery,

19:29.120 --> 19:30.820
though their tendency is downwards,

19:31.360 --> 19:35.020
still are raised up and occupy a position which is not their natural one.

19:36.140 --> 19:39.320
In this manner then the elemental parts obey the universal,

19:39.920 --> 19:43.300
for when they have been fixed in any place perforce they remain there,

19:43.300 --> 19:46.560
until again the universal shall sound the signal for dissolution.

19:48.100 --> 19:51.180
Is it not then strange that thy intelligent part only

19:51.180 --> 19:55.000
should be disobedient and discontented with its own place?

19:55.900 --> 19:57.980
And yet no force is imposed on it,

19:58.000 --> 20:00.900
but only those things which are conformable to its nature.

20:01.800 --> 20:05.680
Still it does not submit, but is carried in the opposite direction.

20:06.600 --> 20:09.600
For the movement toward injustice and intemperance,

20:09.600 --> 20:11.840
and to anger and grief and fear,

20:12.320 --> 20:15.400
is nothing else than the act of one who deviates from nature.

20:16.220 --> 20:20.220
And also when the ruling faculty is discontented with anything that happens,

20:20.740 --> 20:22.540
then too it deserts its post.

20:23.100 --> 20:26.500
For it is constituted for piety and reverence toward the gods,

20:26.960 --> 20:28.360
no less than for justice.

20:29.600 --> 20:33.700
For these qualities also are comprehended under the generic term of contentment

20:33.700 --> 20:35.520
with the constitution of things,

20:35.940 --> 20:38.660
and indeed they are prior to acts of justice.

20:41.540 --> 20:44.960
He who has not one and always the same object in life

20:44.960 --> 20:47.700
cannot be one and the same all through his life.

20:48.360 --> 20:52.200
But what I have said is not enough, unless this also is added,

20:52.600 --> 20:54.420
what this object ought to be.

20:55.180 --> 20:59.240
For as there is not the same opinion about all the things which in some way or other

20:59.240 --> 21:01.760
are considered by the majority to be good,

21:02.000 --> 21:03.820
but only about some certain things,

21:03.920 --> 21:06.180
that is, things which concern the common interest,

21:06.760 --> 21:09.480
so also we ought to propose to ourselves

21:09.480 --> 21:12.160
an object which shall be of a common kind,

21:12.420 --> 21:13.780
social and political.

21:14.740 --> 21:17.580
For he who directs all his own efforts to this object

21:17.580 --> 21:19.380
will make all his acts alike,

21:20.060 --> 21:22.380
and thus will always be the same.

21:24.840 --> 21:28.120
Think of the country mouse and of the town mouse,

21:28.560 --> 21:32.100
and of the alarm and trepidation of the town mouse.

21:34.700 --> 21:37.300
Socrates used to call the opinions of the many

21:37.300 --> 21:39.500
by the name of Lameae,

21:39.920 --> 21:41.760
bug-bears to frighten children.

21:43.100 --> 21:45.270
The Lacedaemonians, at their public spectacles,

21:46.340 --> 21:48.370
used to set seats in the shade for strangers,

21:49.240 --> 21:51.400
but themselves sat down anywhere.

21:54.140 --> 21:56.460
Socrates excused himself to Perticus,

21:56.820 --> 21:57.980
for not going to him,

21:57.980 --> 22:02.060
saying it is because I would not perish by the worst of all ends,

22:02.620 --> 22:05.080
that is, I would not receive a favor,

22:05.420 --> 22:07.960
and then be unable to return it.

22:10.160 --> 22:13.220
In the writings of the Ephesians there was this precept,

22:13.920 --> 22:17.060
constantly to think of someone of the men of former times

22:17.060 --> 22:18.300
who practiced virtue.

22:21.020 --> 22:23.420
The Pythagoreans bid us in the morning,

22:23.660 --> 22:24.580
look to the heavens,

22:24.580 --> 22:29.440
that we may be reminded of those bodies which continually do the same things

22:29.440 --> 22:31.780
and in the same manner perform their work,

22:32.240 --> 22:35.360
and also be reminded of their purity and nudity,

22:35.800 --> 22:38.280
for there is no veil over a star.

22:41.220 --> 22:45.100
Consider what a man Socrates was when he dressed himself in a skin

22:45.100 --> 22:48.480
after Xanthippe had taken his cloak and gone out,

22:48.740 --> 22:52.000
and what Socrates said to his friends who were ashamed of him

22:52.000 --> 22:55.020
and drew back from him when they saw him dressed thus.

22:57.820 --> 23:02.240
Neither in writing nor in reading will thou be able to lay down rules for others

23:02.240 --> 23:05.980
before thou shalt have learned to obey rules thyself.

23:06.440 --> 23:08.700
Much more is this so in life.

23:10.580 --> 23:14.480
A slave thou art, free speech is not for thee.

23:16.140 --> 23:21.040
And my heart laughed within. Odyssey 9.4.13

23:22.400 --> 23:25.480
In virtue they will curse speaking harsh words.

23:26.540 --> 23:28.480
Hesiod works in days 184.

23:30.380 --> 23:33.280
To look for the fig in winter is a madman's act,

23:33.680 --> 23:37.240
such as he who looks for his child when it is no longer allowed.

23:37.980 --> 23:40.500
Epictetus 3.24.87

23:42.160 --> 23:45.320
When a man kisses his child, said Epictetus,

23:45.700 --> 23:47.260
he should whisper to himself,

23:47.920 --> 23:50.100
Tomorrow perchance thou wilt die.

23:50.620 --> 23:52.840
But those are words of bad omen.

23:53.580 --> 23:56.540
No word is a word of bad omen, said Epictetus,

23:57.180 --> 23:59.060
which expresses any work of nature.

23:59.660 --> 24:03.000
Or, if it is so, it is also a word of bad omen

24:03.000 --> 24:05.900
to speak of the ears of corn being reaped.

24:06.980 --> 24:09.360
Epictetus 3.24.88

24:11.360 --> 24:15.680
The unripe grape, the ripe bunch, the dried grape,

24:16.120 --> 24:18.360
all are changes, not into nothing,

24:18.860 --> 24:21.660
but into something which exists not yet.

24:22.300 --> 24:24.500
Epictetus 3.24.

24:26.740 --> 24:28.980
No man can rob us of our free will.

24:29.860 --> 24:32.500
Epictetus 3.22.105

24:34.820 --> 24:36.440
Epictetus also said,

24:36.440 --> 24:39.480
A man must discover an art, or rules,

24:39.980 --> 24:41.940
with respect to giving his assent.

24:42.560 --> 24:44.220
And in respect to his movements,

24:44.320 --> 24:47.800
he must be careful that they be made with regard to circumstances,

24:48.400 --> 24:50.540
that they be consistent with social interests,

24:51.160 --> 24:53.520
that they have regard to the value of the object.

24:54.240 --> 24:55.980
And as to sensual desire,

24:56.560 --> 24:58.780
he should altogether keep away from it.

24:59.060 --> 25:00.380
And as to avoidance,

25:00.620 --> 25:02.980
he should not show it with respect to any of the things

25:02.980 --> 25:04.540
which are not in our power.

25:07.300 --> 25:08.920
The dispute then, he said,

25:09.480 --> 25:11.180
is not about any common matter,

25:11.720 --> 25:14.020
but about being mad or not.

25:17.020 --> 25:18.360
Socrates used to say,

25:18.480 --> 25:21.860
What do you want, souls of rational men or irrational?

25:22.580 --> 25:23.960
Souls of rational men.

25:24.260 --> 25:27.580
Of what rational men? Sound or unsound? Sound.

25:28.200 --> 25:30.140
Why then do you not seek for them?

25:30.260 --> 25:31.500
Because we have them.

25:31.500 --> 25:35.540
Why then do you fight and quarrel?

25:37.180 --> 25:38.880
End of chapter 11.

